segments.text: This is testing testing one two three four one two three four testing testing this is April the 23rd and I'm at 4000 Las Vegas in El Paso and I have the honor of recording the memories of Mr. Anthony Haddad class of 49 to begin with describe your family background
who came from where, when, and then go ahead and just give a biographical summary of you before you went to A&M.
Okay.
I was born in December 20, 1928, in Juarez, Mexico.
My parents were of Syrian descent.
They were in Juarez, in Mexico, because at that time, immigration was very limited for Middle Easterners.
And they spent five years there waiting for their quota number so they could come across.
And I was born while they were waiting.
And I had a sister that was born at the same time.
They came from the old country with four of my brothers and sisters that were born there.
Then when we moved over here in 1930, I had two other sisters that were born on this side.
So we're real international.
I went to school.
We grew up My dad was a peddler Started out as a peddler when he came from the old country didn't know how to speak English didn't know anything but went out and knocked on doors and
peddled, got enough money to open a little grocery store.
Where?
What part of town?
On the south side.
Second Ward, you know, the worst part of town.
He was there for three or four years.
Then he moved up to Yandel, about where St. Clement Church is now, about 700 block.
Had a partner and he had that store for a couple of years.
And I remember when
We had moved to 1400 Yandel, and I was, what, five years old, maybe.
I used to cry to let him take me to the store with him, you know.
And he would, and about halfway there, I'd tell him I was tired, and he'd put me, he was a big man, he'd put me on his shoulders and carry me the rest of the way.
Then he was there two or three years, and then in 1932,
We moved to, our home was 1400 Yandel.
We tore the porch off and daddy built a store in front of the front of the front of our house.
Now this was a little grocery store.
Yeah, a little grocery store, 20 by 40.
And that supported us for until 1954.
We had that store until 1954.
I went to Lamar School.
It was right there.
What language did you speak first?
You know, I think I spoke Arabic first, because my mother never learned to speak English.
She learned a little bit of Spanish, not much, because she stayed home.
You know, she wasn't exposed to anybody.
So I think I learned Arabic first.
Of course, I've forgotten most of it.
And then I went to school with mostly Mexican people, and so I learned Spanish from them.
And then my sisters, I think I learned most of my English from my sisters, my older sisters.
They were all very intelligent.
They used to talk school at home.
Two of my sisters were valedictorians in grammar school and high school.
One of my sisters was a salutatorian.
So they were all smarter than I was, but these three were exceptionally smart, and I think that's where I learned my English.
I went to Lamar through the eighth grade.
Then I went to El Paso High.
Now the student body at El Paso High then, how diverse was it?
It was not as diverse as it is now, you know.
Not as many Spanish-speaking.
A few, yeah.
A lot of the Jewish people were there because they lived right up on Rim Road and right around there.
We had a good Jewish student body.
And then us, we were, you know, I don't know, 30 or 40 of us, you know.
Great school, wonderful experience, great people.
We had a good football team then, too.
Finished there.
The war started
while I was in high school.
Yeah, I was a freshman, I think, in 1941.
So we just went all through high school.
And then a cousin and I got to thinking about college our senior year.
We had a cousin, Art Abraham, that played football at A&M and had gone there and talked it up quite a bit.
So we decided to go there.
Now, what year is your high school graduation?
What year?
46, okay.
I was a Frog at A&M.
Okay.
We graduated in January of 46 and went on right to A&M, you know.
Oh.
I was a midterm.
A Frog, they used to call them that.
I don't know what they call them now.
It still is.
It's still a Frog.
Now, you had not visited there at all.
Never had been there, never knew anything about it, except that that's where we wanted to go.
Didn't know anything about the spirit, didn't know anything.
Now, were you the first of your brothers and your sisters to go to college?
No, no.
Two of my valedictorian sisters went, but neither one of them finished.
One of them got married, and the other one just decided she didn't want to go to college.
All right, so when you went in January of 46,
What did you, you went on the train?
No, we, my cousin's parents drove us.
Oh.
What did you take with you?
What kind of stuff?
Oh, I took, you know, mostly clothes, you know.
I'd never been away from home.
This was quite an experience.
Where had you been?
How far had you traveled anywhere?
Yeah, Juarez.
I think we went to Rio Dosa one time.
You hadn't been to Albuquerque?
No.
Not to Austin?
Nowhere.
Nowhere.
This was the first time.
You know, I remember we were in the grocery business, and we worked it ourselves.
It was a family business, and it was small, and so we just worked.
And when I got there, and once we got into things, it was a surprise in my life.
Did your mother or dad give you any...
Kind of last-minute advice, or...?
Daddy opened a checking account for me.
And he said, spend all you want.
It was a local one.
But he would get the statement And and here in El Paso, you know, he said spend all you want anything you need But the first time I came home he said now what was this for?
What was that for?
So I I watched myself that you had worked in the store.
Yes, but you didn't get paid Working as part of your family.
Yeah, yeah, yeah except

into you know my sophomore junior year my brother also had a store two or three miles on montana street away from us and he got drafted and when he got drafted my sister one of my sisters went and ran the store for me and so i used to go after school i used to go out there and work with her so i worked with her for a couple of years you had made good grades in high school uh yeah not as good as i should have
My counselor came up to me one time and she says, you know, your IQ is 126.
You've got the second highest IQ in the class.
Why aren't you making those kind of grades?
Of course, I wasn't studying, you know.
When you went to A&M, what did you think you were going to major in?
Engineering.

why i just was fascinated by math but i had no background i didn't take any physics i didn't take any chemistry in high school so when i arrived and went to my first chemistry class there was like 300 students in there and i didn't know what they were talking about you know so after about a week i changed my major i changed it to business okay all right describe uh you you go with family
And they take you to the campus.
Do you remember where they let you out?
I don't remember.
Did you have a foot locker already?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I had a foot locker.
And you had some clothes.
What else did you have in that foot locker?
I think maybe some shaving stuff and stuff like that, but I think that's all.
How did you know what unit, what outfit you were going to be in?
How did you know what dormitory?
I guess we must have gotten something in the mail.

uh it's been so long ago i really i really don't remember that part you know so describe getting into the dorm and into your outfit and into your room yeah well we we got there and we were roommates my cousin and i for the first couple of years everything was real nice you know everybody was
real cooperative, real nice, and told us what we needed to do and all that.
Of course, we were mid-term.
What outfit were you in?
A battery, field artillery.
Was it in the Duncan area?
Yeah.
New Dorm?
Yeah.
I don't remember which one, but it was one of those.
We were at the band.
I think the band was above us.
Describe how you all organized your room.
What was in it?
There was a bunk bed, you know, a sink, and a desk, maybe two.
But my cousin made it real clear that I was in charge of fixing the beds, cleaning the room, and I did.
And I think it was good for me, you know, because at home I never did anything, you know, six sisters.
All right, how was a second semester frog treated by the sophomores and the other freshmen?
Mostly, you know, just like they treated the fish, except they never let you forget that you were a frog, you know.
And how did you learn about all the the spirit the traditions how did they?

well, it just the people, you know, the people would talk about it and Yet I'd see him and hear him and you know, finally I you can't help getting into it, you know Where did you have to stand in line to go get your uniforms?
I?

know i don't everything was so hazy the first week or two i just did i just kind of you know imagine i know we had to get sheets and towels they they furnished all of that now there must have been lots of world war ii veterans this is when they first were starting to come come back and it was then i think
six or seven thousand were were in the corps and the veterans were just just began to come back.
We called them non-regs.
How long before they lined you all up in the hallway and this that and the other?
Oh I think just about a week.
I didn't get a spanking for
Gosh, I'll bet you it's three or four weeks before they've got a spanking.
And what kind of paddle did they use?
They used a pretty good size one.
Just, you know, made out of, I guess, a half inch or something like that.
Homemade, you know.
Some of them had holes in them and some of them didn't.
But it never, never hurt.
as much as you thought it was going to, you know?
And it was nice.
It was nice.
I'm really thankful for what I learned there.
Little old innocent boy, you know, didn't know anything, had never been away from home, and it was really, and still is, I think, the best experience of my life.
How long before you got a nickname?
Oh, gosh, pretty quick.
What was it?
Frog head in, head in.
Head in, head in.
Yeah.
Any background as to where they got the head in?
Okay, okay.
And do you remember any things in the dining hall?
Oh, yeah, sure.
Share some of those.
Oh, gosh, yeah.
The food was good.
It really was for, you know, the college.
We sat at the same seat every meal.
The seniors served themselves first, and then the juniors, and we served them too.
You know, we'd pass them stuff and everything.
And then we'd eat.
But there was always at least one of everything for everybody.
It's not like they hogged it or anything.
It was fair.
But we served ourselves last.
Then after we finished eating, if there was anything left, we could have anything we wanted.
And mostly bread and gravy.
Lube, they called it.
And that was fun.
And the food, I thought, for college and cafeteria, I mean, it was always seated, too.
We always sat.
We marched in.
And then I think we just walked out, you know.
But we always marched, everybody in front of their building, and marched in, and most of the time the band would play.
Describe a typical day.
What time did you get up?
What did you do when between getting up and going to bed at night?
Gosh, yeah, let's see.

we used to get up pretty early or i would i'd get up pretty early usually at six o'clock or so and i still do you know we'd wash up clean up i'd fix the beds clean straighten out the room we'd fall in for breakfast after breakfast we'd come back get our books go to class come back you know i don't know i think
I think we fell in for lunch, too.
I'm not sure.
I know we did for the evening meal.
We might have just gone to the mess hall for lunch.
I don't remember.
But we always sat together, you know, the same group every time.
We'd have lunch, go back to class, come back home.
Intramural sports, sometimes we'd go out and play, you know, football, volleyball.
I know as a freshman, we had PE.
We had to take PE.
We had that 1.2 mile run we had to do every day, and we had to do it within a certain time.
By and large, where did that run?
What was the route?
I think it was around the track.
Okay.
Yeah.
At Kyle Field?
At Kyle Field or around there, maybe some practice field around there or something.
Then we'd come home, study, and then, of course, you know, shoot the breeze all the time, you know, get together.
Maybe the freshmen would get together and shoot the breeze, talk about what had happened, what was going on, rumors, you know.
Now, you weren't allowed to have a radio, were you, as a freshman?
I didn't have one.
No, I didn't know whether we were allowed to or not.
I didn't have one.
And no typewriter?

yeah oh you had a typewriter yes i did you took it with you oh yeah that's right i took one with me my dad bought me a little underwood portable that's right i did have a typewriter uh the uh uh the courses were there some of those first semester courses that you now realize were important in shaping anything well when i switched over to business the spanish the english the math i felt like i'd had it before

you know it was all pretty pretty easy for me in the history but after that you know statistics and all that then it really got interesting the first that first spring semester did you come home for easter or did you stay there the whole spring i think i came home yeah how did you i used to hitchhike a lot after they told me how to do it and all that but i don't think i did it my first
my first semester, I think after my sophomore year.
Then I started, I used to hitchhike home.
We'll talk about that in a minute, because I want to get good hitchhiking stories.
Yeah, that was really something.
And you communicated, particularly that first semester, did you write letters back and forth?
Mostly letters.

you know i didn't call much i don't know whether we even had a phone in the house i don't think we had a phone in the house we had a phone in the store because we delivered and did all that but i didn't i don't think we had a phone at home what do you think you told them about life at a m that first semester well i didn't tell them the truth i tell you i was um i was in a state of shock almost you know but uh and i came home one time and
I was taking a shower, and my mama saw my rear end, and it was red.
And she said, what happened?
I said, oh, I fell, mama.
But I didn't get, we didn't get.
Did your dad, did your dad?
My dad never saw it.
He didn't ask?
No.
It's just how is it, you know, and he checked on the money, and you know.
But we didn't, it didn't happen very often.
It really didn't.
So when that first semester,

you passed everything yeah but you didn't do as well as you wanted to in chemistry well i didn't i dropped that my first week remember i switched over to business oh okay yeah and that's why i say it was so easy you know regular and so that first semester went well academically oh yeah yeah right you came home for the summer yeah what'd you do that summer do you remember um i i worked in the store okay or did i work you know i i
My dad didn't need me.
I think I drove a car for an elderly lady that was a welcome wagon.
And I drove her around during the summer.
All right, then you go back for the fall.
Same roommate.
Yeah.
Same outfit.
Yeah.
Well, it was a battery.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah since Since it was only your second semester Were you treated like a sophomore or a freshman?
We were supercharged they called it.
Oh, okay We were supercharged freshmen.
We had to stay with our class.
Mm-hmm, you know, so describe the routine for a sophomore then I
Well, you know what they called us.
Should I say it?
It doesn't matter.
Pissheads.
Well, we just kind of copied what the guys before us did.
We kept order.
We made a lot of noise.
Did you ever paddle any fish?
A couple, I think, yeah.

for what do you remember anything no i don't i don't remember all right then describe the routine for football games by then oh boy yeah yeah gosh i don't think we marched in but we went we had to stand up during the whole game never sit down
And I don't know whether we had to stoop all the time or not.
You know how we used to do like this?
I don't know whether we did that just when we yelled or we did it all the time.
You went to Yale practice?
Oh, yeah.
Never missed.
You know, that got to be a habit.
Yeah, we had to go.
We went.
And those were good.
And did you make any of the core trips that fall?
Yeah.
Yeah, I made them all.
Where?
How did you go to those Houston and Austin and Dallas and Fort Worth?
You know, I think, was it our sophomore year or our junior year, my cousin got a car.
And we used to drive.
And when I wasn't with him, I'd hitchhike.
Now, coming home, I'd hitchhike.
Because most of the time, like midterm,
Most of my exams, I didn't have to take my finals.
You know how they used to do.
Because you were making good grades.
Yeah, yeah.
And I forgot what they called it.
Anyway, so... A distinguished student.
Well, yeah.
You were a DS.
For two semesters, I was a distinguished student.
But all the other semesters, I didn't have to take very many finals, you know.
And he did, so I'd hitchhike home.
And that was an experience.
How long did it take to hitchhike from College Station to El Paso?
You know, not that long.
What route would you normally take?
Usually I'd go...
Did you go to Austin or San Antonio?
Austin.
Yeah, I think I'd go through Austin.
And, you know, I never stayed at a place too long.
Really had good luck.
Did you have any memorable experiences?
Well, just, you know, one time I got in the car with a guy, and he had a bottle of whiskey and a gun.
But he was really, really nice.
He offered me a drink.
And the gun was between us, you know, like.
And he drove me, I think, from, I don't know, Austin, all the way to El Paso.
Did you ever have any bad experience hitchhiking?
You know, I never did.
I never did.
I have not, in all these interviews, had a bad one yet.
No, there's nothing that I remember that even close to bad.
A few people have said, well, he may have been driving a little too fast.
Or maybe he had a little too much to drink.
Two or three of them have said, I was asked to drive.
We did once for a lady.
My cousin and I had both hitchhiked together that time, and she was wasted.
All right.
When you were leaving El Paso to go back, where was the best place to catch a ride?
You know, I don't know whether I hitchhiked back or not.

don't remember going that way i think i used to just hitchhike home and then i'd either take a train or a bus all right if you took the train where did you go to at union depot and uh to dallas okay and then go and then down okay yeah if you took the bus what route you know i don't think i ever took the bus because i don't remember but my my folks wouldn't let me hitchhike back in those
First year or two, did you have any dates over there?
No.
No.
You know, I hadn't had much to do with girls, really.
And you and your buddies, what was it like to work on Bonfire that first fall?
Oh, that was really good.
We just worked.

now that that's one of the first years y'all cut down some trees there were logs yeah they were it was a big big bonfire all right i remember as far as i know that's the first year they really used logs isn't that something where where were you working were you part of the cutting crew or the whole no i was by the bonfire you were helping the stack yeah yeah and it was on the drill field
I don't remember.
I think that's where it was.
Probably.
And about how long in weeks did y'all work on it?
Gosh, I don't remember that either.
A long time, I know.
I don't know.
Did you work much at night?
I didn't.
I think I worked mostly afternoons.
I don't remember it being dark while we were working.
Did anybody get hurt?
No.
Nobody that I was aware of, you know.
Was there any drinking too much or anything like that?
I never saw any.
But like I tell you, you know, I was an innocent kid.
And what did you, how did you feel when that bonfire was lit?
Oh, gosh.
It was unbelievable.
I didn't, I didn't think anybody could do that, you know.
When did the A&M spirit begin, did you begin to feel the spirit?
Oh, gosh.
You know, I think really I didn't really get into it until I got home that summer.
That first spring?
Yeah.
Yeah, I didn't, because most of the time I was, you know, nervous and wondering whether I was going to go back.
You know, but after I got home, I missed it.

did you make some friendships early that were lasting oh yeah yeah i did not not many but i have my my senior year uh was a good friend uh jim stevens he's our class uh agent our class agent now and uh he's a good friend he was uh
I think he was in the band above us.
Anytime he comes to El Paso, he stops by.
I've seen him last year a couple of times.
I haven't seen him this year yet.
Now, back before the war, they had a day in the spring called Fish Day.
when everything reversed.
Was there a fish day in your area?
Well, I was a frog, see?
So I never got that fish experience.
Okay.
Yeah, and I know they didn't have a frog day.
Do they still walk in the gutter, the freshmen, or...?
If so, I'm not aware of it.
We used to have to walk in the gutter.
I don't believe they do anymore.
Who did you go to for academic advice of what to take and not to take?
Nobody.
Who were some of the, as you changed to business, who were some of the teachers that were important to you in business?
Well, Dr. Nance in business was, he was a history teacher.
You had Dr. Nance?
Yeah.
I graded papers for him.
Really?
Yeah.
He's the department head that hired me.
Make believe I didn't know Dr. Nance.
Describe Dr. Nance.
Well, to me, he was all business.
He was a good teacher.
I enjoyed history with him.
I guess he saw that I did because he asked me after one semester with him if I'd like to grade papers for him, you know.
And I told him yes.
I don't know what it paid, not much, but it was something to do because, you know, I didn't
I didn't get out.
I didn't carouse.
I had a little time on my hands.
I liked him a lot.
He was not flamboyant or anything like that.
He was just a good teacher.
He didn't smile very often, but... Where was his office then?
Do you remember?
Where was history?
It was in one of the older buildings, you know, but I don't...
See, when I got there, it was a Nagel Hall.
I think that's... Really?
I think that's the one.
Oh, okay.
The old civil engineering building.
Uh-huh.
Okay.
Yeah.
Let me turn... Yeah.
There are some other, some people you remember in business that were... Well, there was the business cycles teacher, and I forgot his name.
He was a small man,
Drove an old, old car.
People used to make fun of him.
Gosh, I wish, and Dr. Stevenson in statistics, he taught it beautifully.
Gosh, it was so interesting.
I didn't want to leave his class, you know.
That was real good.
Mr. Hoyle, business law, he was good.
Who else did I have?
Did you go to class regularly?
I never missed, except my senior year, I had an insurance class that was at 8 o'clock in the morning, and I was in the non-regs then.
I didn't get a contract with the military, and I don't know why I'd oversleep and I'd miss his class.
I got a D, the first D I ever got.
And I deserved it.
But until then, you went regularly?
Oh, yes.
And even then, I did, except for that one class.
How did you and your buddies behave in class?
Pretty good.
Pretty good.
I don't remember anybody cutting up or anything.
No, I think, yeah, real good.
Might have been that military, you know, because I don't remember anybody being disciplined.
